<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The analogy of the English language requires that the
noun and verb which are pronounced alike should agree in spelling. Thus
we have <xex>notice</xex> (n. & v.), <xex>noticed</xex>,
<xex>noticing</xex>, <xex>noticer</xex>; <xex>poultice</xex> (n. & v.);
<xex>apprentice</xex> (n. & v.); <xex>office</xex> (n. & v.),
<xex>officer</xex> (n.); <xex>lattice</xex> (n.), <xex>latticed</xex>
(a.); <xex>benefice</xex> (n.), <xex>beneficed</xex> (a.), etc. Cf.
<xex>sacrifice</xex> (<?/; n. & v.), <xex>surmise</xex> (<?/; n. & v.),
<xex>promise</xex> (<?/; n. & v.); <xex>compromise</xex> (<?/; n. & v.),
etc. Contrast <xex>advice</xex> (<?/; n.), and <xex>advise</xex> (<?/);
<xex>device</xex> (<?/), and <xex>devise</xex> (<?/), etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

